A Republican Strategy to Combat the Reelection of Obama
The Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Centre considers this to be a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is more rare in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In addition, Republican lawyers have identified only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
In this spirit, a majority of U.S. governments promulgated new laws from 2009 that made the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon took on an increase after the November 2010 elections, which included 675 new Republican representatives in 26 States.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 States were introduced in the only year of 2011.
New electoral laws require electors to present an identity card with photos and evidence of American citizenship.
Moreover, these laws also reduce voting periods in advance, invalidate the right to register as an elector on election day and withdraw citizens with a judicial record from their right to vote.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a requirement.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirms in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indian law.
The republican authorities began to extend this practice to other States.
Over the past two years, they sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, 21 million people of voting age, do not have identity cards with pictures issued by a government agency of their state.
In addition, five million new electors in 2012 do not have such an identity.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to get the required ID card.
New restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of Afro-Americans, 15% of people earning less than 35,000 dollars; 18% of citizens over 65 years of age and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required identity card with a photo.
Much more.
Students, voters considered to be more voting for democratic candidates, are not allowed in a number of States to use their identity card with photos issued by their institutions.
On the other hand, these same States allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use to vote the cards issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to present such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly designed to limit the Hispanic vote.
It appears, however, that two Spanish voters out of three favour the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican legislators sponsored in 2011 laws abolishing voter registration on polling day in eight States.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to electors wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the recording of approximately 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 dropped the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have adopted legislation in five other States to reduce the voting period in advance.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were Afro-Americans, while they represented only 13% of the electors in the state.
It was the same with the Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites who formed 76% of voters accounted for only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of electors.
Several bills were blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit the damage in part.
For example, only 16 out of 34 States have adopted laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID card.
Nevertheless, the new rules in place will undoubtedly make exercising the right to vote more difficult in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see a clear objective of influencing results in 2012 in key States.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Centre shows that States that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to assert with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have significant impacts on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
