Unless a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that exchanged bitcoins exist well in the public account book, broadcast across the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers, and the winner of which, as a temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a file-hashing phase, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and more unique fingerprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "make" the whole.
The aim is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check that it's the right one.
The transaction is thus indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the print.
If, to cheat, one user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other left orphan because both have different fingerprints.
The computer has solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to 100 millionth, leaving the margin...
The challenge is also seen in each increase in the calculation power.
