Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of this agency, the second Member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had begun close collaboration with the ESA in 1994 and in the years that followed participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, Poland's road to space started much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always find an understanding.
For example, I would like to refer to A. Šternfeld's conference at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas drawn from his cutting-edge work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born 1905) left the cold listeners and years later Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
Lédit Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in the Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a propagator of the world-renowned astronaut, his contribution has been rewarded in particular by the fact that his name has been given to one of the craters on the hidden side of the Moon.
As early as 1925, a stream was built in Poland to be equipped with a fused engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
Nor is it clear if the rocket was to be used to propell or brake the drase.
The only known information about this stream is that of the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to the rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komorka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the retained documents that this research had reached the test stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the research stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photo-electronic hunting rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakiethobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywobblelocki.
Both projects aimed at military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects to use rocket technology were carried out by the Interim Advisory Scientific Committee ("Tymczasowy Committeee Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works devoted to the aircraft were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautic Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a company in the November 1954 issue of the Journal Problem, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to the aeronautical industry.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create an Astronautic Society
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautic Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the international Astronautic Federation (created in 1951) and in the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice-President of the International Astronautical Federation.
He kept his job until his death in 1959.
From 1956 onwards, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological fusion, which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version was built, RM-1A and, during the summer of 1959, two-storey RM-2 flight tests were started in the Bledov desert.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 meters and was probably 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have ranged up to 14.5 km and served to observe the wind at altitude.
In 1963, however, all development work was halted.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, followed by the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A fusion had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these gear types was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
The entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Commission for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later should also be mentioned.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
