The film Argo: When everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a number of demonstrators composed of Islamist students attacked the American Embassy of Tehran and held in hostages 52 diplomats.
They were to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had been supporting his regime for decades.
The situation did not offer the U.S. administration a positive outcome, it could not, indeed, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously undermined the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a hard blow for the prestige of the United States, even worsened later by the fiasco of the attempt to release hostages by force.
The sequestered diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian Government.
Their fate in the United States sparks a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment.
The Iranian debacle strongly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, by the actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offers a small victory in America.
Just before she was occupied, six employees escaped the embassy.
After complicated peripeties, they found themselves in the Ambassador of Canada's residence.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran with a rocambolesque cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a shooting team to make screenings for a large-scale science-fiction film.
Combination of genders
The expert's plan on exfiltration Tony Mendez requires Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation were long kept secret, and the film was based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is a part of a political thriller designed in a realistic way but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful coup, a betrayal - such as in the Ocean's high trilogy, twelve and thirteen.
The ambience follows: sequences of documentary-style Tehran (in the sequences under title are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and the way in which, thanks to these pictures, these same situations have been rewritten in the film, there are no great differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a bit of exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, corridors and telephone...
Ben Affleck managed to re-start his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculous actor, he became a respected director and his acting game ceased to raise ironic remarks.
Argo is his third long film after the dark police officer " Gone Baby Gone " (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It's also Affleck's first film that doesn't take place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the embassy's fall is impressive by its clarity that also suggests confusion and unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a history page is written.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect in fictional scenes (the false shooting team in the Teheran bazaar).
Too many actions to too many places
The director had to be content with a subject offering only a few striking scenes in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It is very good, it sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is separated by a telephone shot in America and the pursuit on the landing runway is quite pulled by the hair).
The weakness of Argo lies in its dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events to too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-ops, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from there, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a little dramatic tension, it is seen with moderate interest, appreciating the realization and retro style of the 70's.
He's training the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of still history, in a certain way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of secret services as omnipotent and omnidents, he does the matter.
