Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert in relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think she doesn't support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, however, without being overly critical of Israel.
At the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen the abstention at the vote on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposes this measure.
Does Germany have difficulty in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy that is defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of consistent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore clash with several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to find that role, but they are on the path to a "more normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, such as France or Great Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It expresses the desire to adopt positions independent of those in the United States and European partners, including with regard to national dossiers.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, so by exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position regarding the conflict in the Middle East and the abstention at the United Nations vote?
First, Germany has important outlets in the Near East, especially in the Gulf countries.
This is why Berlin must take care not to offend public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is without a doubt a decisive element.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, as this is not a purely unilateral relationship.
But this is, in any case, a decisive element in the German strategic reflections.
Does Germany concern relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that the Europeans and the Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will only be respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
The United States, on the other hand, announced their veto with a clear voice.
Do the views differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, of course, the government cannot defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great that they always seem so.
If you observe the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from engulfing with enthusiasm for Netanyahu's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners on the other?
I don't think it's easy for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today that is not the case.
They cannot therefore enter a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are doing in the issue of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will play a role in the future as a locomotive and will encourage Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not simple for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been delicate.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware that they have to play a role that marks their independence more.
Germany is playing a role as a major player on the international stage, and does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or is it always difficult to take on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still has difficulty playing a more important role.
If one looks, for example, at the euro crisis, it is noted that whenever Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
In fact, it is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed of very varied neighbours and opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only diminishing, but at the moment the EU does not fill this void, while it remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant for them and if they're only less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy of Washington, an institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Market Protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well known brands all over the world.
Armani Polo... what is this really about?
Behind this name is a trade mark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys protection such as the company bearing the name of the trade mark cannot lodge a complaint.
And even if she could, she's not sure she'd get a cause win.
"It's increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China," says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing's office specialized in violating property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file comes to my office.
The copywriters need only a few additional letters to be able to record their trademarks.
Thus, instead of Gucci, we register Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we register Prada-Kny.
