The hardest trade in the world: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through the steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who work literally in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 minors who earn their lives by carrying the sulphur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
He must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfuric gas emanating from the earth's roots is solidified in contact with the air.
After collecting large sulphur rocks, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep trails.
There are only 250 meters up to the top of the volcano that peaks at 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a tortoise all, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so that they do not stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their life, as it happened to a French tourist who had a deadly fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The minors of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents of euro for each kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once on the top, they cross a path between tourists photographing them as if they were circus animals, and carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometres to the balance that a mining company has installed a little on the counter at 1,850 meters altitude.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euro) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it at 10,000 rupees (83 cents of euro) to the petrochemical industry as this mineral is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who generally travels three trips a day.
Everyone takes 3 hours and ends up exhausted, but this allows them to earn 138,000 rupees (11,50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such an overhuman effort, it is the triple of what he would gain in the fields.
"The income of minors is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (€1.20) per day and where the average monthly wage is two million rupees (€167)," says the carrier who used to work as a mason on the island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not as difficult, but then he returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as the sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I took her to Java for conversion to Islam."
Then he has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27 years of age, he spent three of his life challenging the danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulphur had already started making him pay the bill although he covered his face with a mask and wore special gloves.
Then he has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases rejected by the volcano.
It's the price he has to pay to continue his dream.
"I'm going to work another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French" he promises in a more acceptable English than acceptable.
Sick of life, this friendly and intelligent young person could be a tour guide, server or receptionist in a hotel, but, instead, he does the work of a mule.
He shares an unhealthy wood measurement with other carriers, rises every day at two hours in the morning because the sulphur keeps freezing at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
