Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Basket-ball is my whole life"
The "Hetin" Reyes basketball tractor has spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the land and, thanks to him, has traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as big as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a brain hemorrhage condemned him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, a national basketball team player, manager and leader of the national team, BSN, with the Bayamón Vacaros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I carried several helmets in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the National Team and President of the Federation during the 1990s," Reyes recalls during a first hour visit to his home in Bayamón, where he lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basket-ball is my whole life."
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes that statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and souvenirs that recall his itinerary out of order, testify.
Bayamón in the heart
Out of all his memories, the ones he loves most are those who remind him of his passage as a player in the Vacaros team in the mid-50s until 1982, after having spent 15 years as a co-manager or manager of the team.
"This has been my best years, the ones I've enjoyed most because I've had the chance to participate in eight cowboy championships since 1967, be it manager, co-manager or leader.
This has been a lot of years of satisfaction, including the five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
Then I retired at the 1981 championship, the year that Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead of the team," says Reyes.
I remember that Gene Bartow, who had been the leader here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me, "I have a rough player for you, it's two meters.
